<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-04-08T21:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-04-08T21:00:00-05:00" n="537" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d537">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/13454: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Counselor of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Peck</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-04-09T10:00:00+08:00">April 9, 1936—10
                                a.m.</date><lb/>[Received April 9—2:05 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>86. This office’s 81, April 6, 11 a.m.<note n="70" xml:id="d537fn70">Not
                                printed.</note></p>
                        <list>
                            <label>1.</label>
                            <item>Foreign Office states that it has this morning received a telegram
                                from Shansi authorities stating that the sieges of Linfen (Pingyang)
                                and Hungtung were raised on April 2 and 4, respectively. The foreign
                                missionaries at those places are “quite safe” and continued
                                protection is being afforded them.</item>
                            <label>2.</label>
                            <item>Repeated to Peiping, Tientsin, Shanghai.</item>
                        </list>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Peck</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>